		<h2 id="lesson1">Section 1 Notes: World Wide Web</h2>
		<div class="information" id="lesson1-1">
			<div class="information-title">
				WWW
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					world wide web - information space where web resources are identified by URLs, which are accessed via the internet. The web pages are made of text documents that are formatted using HTML (hyper text markup language)
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-nd000/l-3873828673/e-48230539/m-48742046">This video</a> does a good job of explaining this.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="information" id="lesson1-2">
			<div class="information-title">
				HTML
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					<em>HTML</em>, the main type of document on the web, which glues everything together. The web uses HTTP <em>(Hypertext Transfer Protocol)</em> in the browser to communcate to the servers.
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-nd000/l-3873828673/m-48724340">This video</a> does a good job in introducing HTML.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="information" id="lesson1-3">
			<div class="information-title">
				Tags and Elements
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					Tags are structured with a less then simbol, the name of the tag, the greater than symbol, the contents, the less than symbol, a backslash, the name of the tag again, then the greater than symbol. The whole tag from the first less than symbol to the last greater than symbol is referred to as the <em>Element</em>.
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-nd000/l-3873828673/m-48723444">This video</a> does a good job in explaining the basics of Tags and Elements.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="information" id="lesson1-4">
			<div class="information-title">
				Computers are Stupid
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					Computers can only understand what is fed to them by a human. Humans might understand small typoes and still understand the whole picture, but computers will crash or do terrible things if small problems are present; such as: no end tag, a spelling error, and other easily correctable mistakes.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="information" id="lesson1-5">
			<div class="information-title">
				Inline and block elements
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					The difference between inline/block is that inline tags do not create a box around the tag, so the height and width of the tagged area cannot be customized. The block tag creates a tag where the box size can be customized.
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-nd000/l-3873828673/m-48723438">This video</a> does a good job in explaining the difference between inline and block.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
