	<div class="lesson">
		<h2 id="lesson3">Section 3 Notes: CSS Style in HTML</h2>
		<div class="information" id="lesson3-1">
			<div class="information-title">
				CSS vs HTML
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					While HTML provides the structure of the web document, CSS provides the style. To add style, you have the HTML document look for a specific CSS style document that corresponds with the HTML document.
				</p>
				<p>
					<a href="https://www.udacity.com/course/viewer#!/c-nd000/l-4131369051/e-3614428682/m-2603798584">This Video</a> does a good job in explaining how the relationship between HTML and CSS works.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="information" id="lesson3-2">
			<div class="information-title">
				Avoiding Repetition
			</div>
			<div class="information-description">
				<p>
					To avoid repetition in coding, it is important to create a CSS file seperate of the HTML file for all the style changes. This makes it much easier to review code, and make changes in a timely manor. It is inefficient to have to skim the HTML file for specific sections that need to be edited. It also help avoid confusion from syntactic errors by avoiding copy-paste errors and makes it easier to keep the style more uniform.
				</p>
			</div>
